This guide is a detailed process for installing Vivado Design Suite and setting up the design environment by learning how to create designs and write and simulate Verilog/SystemVerilog testbenches. 
This document is an easy-to-follow guide to setting up your own environment from scratch, right from the account setup process to simulation execution.

🛠️ Vivado Installation & Setup Guide

🔐 Step 1: Create AMD Account

-> Go to: [https://login.amd.com/app/amd_accountamdcom_1/exk559qg7f4aW4yim697/sso/saml]
-> Create your AMD account (required for download & licensing )

---

⬇️ Step 2: Download Vivado

-> Visit: [https://www.xilinx.com/support/download/index.html/content/xilinx/en/downloadNav/vivado-design-tools.html]

📦 Suggested Versions:

Vivado 2023.1 (Recommended Stable)

  -> Supports many FPGA boards
  -> Limited SystemVerilog support

Vivado 2024.2 / 2025.1

  -> Better SystemVerilog support
  -> Supports fewer FPGA boards

---

⚙️ Step 3: Installation Process

1. Launch installer → Allow "OpenJDK platform binary"
2. Click "Next"

Installation Steps:

* Install Type
  → Login with AMD account
  → Select "Download and Install Now"

---
* Select Product
  → Choose "Vivado"
---
* Edition
  → Select "Vivado ML Standard"
---
* Components Selection

  * Design Tools
    ✔ Vivado Design Suite
    ✔ Vitis HLS
  * Devices
    ✔ 7 Series
    ✔ SoC
    ✔ Engineering Sample Devices (optional)
    ✔ UltraScale (optional)

* License Option
  → Select "Acquire or Manage License Key"
---
* License Agreement
  → Accept all
---

📁 Step 4: Installation Directory

* Choose installation path (ensure sufficient disk space)
* Enable:
  ✔ Create program group entries → "Xilinx Design Tools"
  ✔ Apply to "All Users"

---

⏳ Step 5: Installation Time

* Typically takes **40 minutes to 3 hours** (depends on internet speed and system ram)

---

🚀 Step 6: Launch Vivado

- Method 1:

* Use desktop/start menu shortcut

- Method 2 (if shortcut missing):

```
Installation Directory → Xilinx → <Version> → Vivado → bin → vivado.bat (Windows batch file)
```

* Double-click → Command prompt opens → GUI launches automatically

---

‍💻 Creating Your First Project

📌 Step 7: New Project Setup

* Open Vivado → "Quick Start → Create Project"
* Click "Next"

Configure:

* "Project Name & Location"
---
* "Project Type" → RTL Project
---

📂 Step 8: Add Files

* Design Sources

  * Add only RTL files (Verilog/SystemVerilog)
  * Optionally create new source file

* Simulation Sources

  * Add testbench files separately

* Constraints

  * Optional

---

🧠 Step 9: Select Device

* Default Part Selection:

  * Boards → All
  * Family → Zynq-7000 Series
  * Example: XC7Z010 (any suitable board series clg400,300,200)

---

🧩 Project Management

📁 Adding Files

Go to :Project Manager → Sources → “+”

  * Add Design Sources -> create file -> name your files
  * Add Simulation Sources -> create file -> name your files

---

🔝 Setting Top Module

Right-click file → "Set as Top"

  * Design Sources → Main module
  * Simulation Sources → Testbench

---

▶️ Simulation Flow

## Run Simulation:

From "Flow Navigator"

or use TCL:

```
launch_simulation
```

## Close Simulation:

* Click "X" on simulation window
* OR use TCL:

```
close_sim
```

⚠️ Notes

* Prefer declaring ports directly in code
* Ensure correct top module selection before simulation
* Separate design and testbench files properly
